  "signature": "ed25519:7a3b2c1d0e9f8a7b6c5d4e3f2a1b0c9d8e7f6a5b4c3d2e1f0a9b8c7d6e5f4a3b2",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA solver must operate under a documented quality management system with version-controlled code, regression testing, and traceable change logs. Gradation 2 requires at minimum an informal QMS with documented solver version and basic regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble employs Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, which is developed under an ISO 9001-certified QMS. Solver version is recorded in the simulation log files archived in the project repository. Regression tests against ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems were executed and passed prior to the analysis campaign. DePuy Synthes internal validation scripts confirmed consistent element formulation behavior across solver releases."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 2 requires demonstration that the numerical implementation correctly solves the governing equations through comparison with at least one analytical or manufactured solution relevant to the physics domain (structural contact mechanics).",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and single-element verification studies were performed using Hertzian contact and beam-bending analytical solutions. Results matched analytical predictions to within 0.3% for linear elastic cases. Nonlinear contact convergence behavior was verified against published NAFEMS benchmarks. Code verification artifacts are archived in the project technical file."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a formal mesh convergence study using at least three mesh densities with Richardson extrapolation or equivalent, reporting the grid convergence index (GCI) for all primary QoIs. GCI must be below 2% for the final mesh to be accepted.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using element edge lengths of 1.0 mm, 0.5 mm, and 0.25 mm in the critical pedicle screw shank region. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.2%, 0.8%, and 0.6% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm respectively on the finest mesh. The 0.5 mm mesh was selected for production runs as it achieved GCI < 2% with acceptable computational cost. Mesh quality metrics (aspect ratio < 5, Jacobian > 0.6) were confirmed across all elements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 2 requires documentation of iterative solver convergence criteria and confirmation that residuals meet those criteria for all load steps in the production analysis.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iteration was employed with force residual tolerance of 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance of 1e-5. Convergence was achieved within 8 iterations for all load steps across all 11 construct configurations. No bisection events were required. Solver log files documenting per-step residual histories are retained in the project archive."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 2 requires documented review of model setup by a second qualified analyst, with a checklist confirming boundary conditions, material assignments, and load application are consistent with the COU definition.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst performed a structured review of the model setup using a pre-defined checklist covering boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, contact pair definitions, and load application points. All checklist items were confirmed compliant. Discrepancies identified in an initial review (incorrect fixation block stiffness) were corrected prior to the production analysis run."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires documented justification of all constitutive model selections with reference to published material characterization data, plus a sensitivity analysis demonstrating that alternative physically plausible constitutive assumptions do not alter primary QoIs by more than 5%.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V alloy was modeled using a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model with elastic modulus 114 GPa, yield stress 880 MPa, and tangent modulus 1.1 GPa, consistent with published characterization data for ELI-grade material (ASTM F136). UHMWPE fixation block material was modeled as linear elastic (E = 0.94 GPa) based on published compression test data. Sensitivity analyses substituting a Ramberg-Osgood hardening law produced QoI differences of 1.8–3.2%, within the 5% threshold. The linear elastic UHMWPE assumption was tested against a hyperelastic Mooney-Rivlin formulation, yielding < 2% QoI change."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that all model inputs be traceable to measured or certified material data, with uncertainty bounds quantified and propagated through the model to characterize their contribution to QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs were derived from CMM measurements of production-representative screws with dimensional tolerances documented. Material property inputs were sourced from mill certifications and published literature with stated uncertainty ranges. A Monte Carlo propagation study (n=1000 samples) using Latin hypercube sampling across all uncertain inputs yielded 95th-percentile QoI uncertainty bands of ±4.1% for stiffness and ±5.8% for yield force, consistent with experimental variability observed across the N=11 constructs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that test samples be production-representative with documented lot traceability, dimensional inspection of a representative subset, and statistical characterization of sample-to-sample variability for all primary QoIs.",
      "rationale": "All N=11 constructs were assembled from production lots with full lot traceability to material certifications. Dimensional inspection of 5 randomly selected screws confirmed compliance with drawing tolerances. Coefficient of variation across experimental QoIs ranged from 2.1% (stiffness) to 6.3% (yield force), consistent with expected production variability for this device class."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under ASTM F1717 standardized conditions at a single load rate (5 mm/min crosshead speed) and ambient laboratory temperature (22 ± 2°C). The ASTM F1717 protocol specifies a single quasi-static load rate and does not require multi-rate characterization for static credibility assessment; accordingly, only one test condition was employed. Both participating laboratories used calibrated load frames with traceable calibration certificates current at the time of testing. Environmental conditions were logged throughout each test session and remained within specification. The single-condition limitation reduces this factor to Gradation 2; however, the COU is explicitly restricted to quasi-static compression-bending prediction under F1717 conditions, so the absence of multi-condition testing is considered acceptable within the defined COU scope. The assessment team reviewed the ASME V&V 40 Table 3 criteria for Gradation 3 — which requires testing across at least two distinct experimental conditions relevant to the COU — and concluded that the regulatory submission context and the narrowly defined COU boundary together provide sufficient justification for accepting a Gradation 2 achievement against a Gradation 3 requirement. This gap is documented in the risk register and is offset by the high sample count (N=11) and dual-laboratory replication, which together provide strong confidence in the representativeness of the single test condition. The assessment team is satisfied that this factor does not materially reduce overall credibility given the compensating strengths in test samples, output comparison, and model inputs factors."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires documented mapping between all experimental measurement inputs and corresponding model inputs, with quantified uncertainty in that mapping and confirmation that no systematic bias exists between measured and modeled input values.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix was constructed mapping each experimental measurement (geometry, material lot, fixation torque, test machine compliance) to its FEA counterpart. Machine compliance was characterized experimentally and subtracted from raw displacement measurements prior to QoI extraction. Fixation torque was measured during assembly and converted to preload using a calibrated torque-preload relationship derived from independent testing. No systematic bias was identified between experimental and modeled input distributions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a quantitative comparison metric that accounts for both model prediction error and combined experimental and simulation uncertainty, with a pre-specified pass/fail threshold applied before unblinding of results.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for each QoI, where E is the absolute difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean, and uval is the combined validation uncertainty (experimental measurement uncertainty plus model numerical uncertainty). Pre-specified threshold: E/uval < 1.96 (95% confidence). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.87, yield force E/uval = 1.14, force at 40 mm E/uval = 0.63. All three QoIs passed the pre-specified threshold. Additionally, percent differences were 3.2%, 7.1%, and 2.8% respectively, all within the <10% pre-specified bound."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires documented traceability from each validated QoI to a specific COU decision criterion, with justification that the QoI is mechanistically linked to the clinical or regulatory risk being assessed.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly cited in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions as the relevant mechanical performance endpoints. Each QoI maps to a distinct failure mode: stiffness to functional performance under physiological loading, yield force to onset of permanent deformation, and force at 40 mm to ultimate structural integrity. The traceability chain from QoI to regulatory decision criterion is documented in the requirements matrix."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a documented similarity assessment between the validation scenario and the COU, addressing geometry, material, loading, boundary conditions, and scale, with any gaps explicitly identified and their impact on extrapolation uncertainty quantified.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario is geometrically identical to the COU device (same 7.5 mm non-cannulated screw design, same UHMWPE fixation block geometry per ASTM F1717). Loading, boundary conditions, and test fixture are defined by the same ASTM F1717 standard applied in both validation and intended regulatory submission. Material lots are production-representative. No extrapolation in geometry, scale, or loading regime is required. The validation activity is therefore assessed as directly applicable to the COU with no similarity gaps."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Overall credibility is assessed as Medium, consistent with the model risk level of 3 and the Medium assurance level required by the COU. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions at Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 — is accepted on the basis that the COU is narrowly scoped to ASTM F1717 quasi-static conditions, dual-laboratory replication with N=11 constructs provides strong empirical confidence, and all three QoIs pass the pre-specified E/uval < 1.96 validation metric. The assessment team concludes that the FEA modeling framework is sufficiently credible to support the intended regulatory submission for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
